<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-751-610  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 751 610.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 9 1989 v23 n41 pSR23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Practice what you preach. (IS in the 1990s)(corporaterestructuring should encompass IS departments)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Westerman, Jewell G.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corporations must reorganize to take full advantage of informationtechnology.andP;  The historical corporate bureaucracy is beingrendered obsolete by the ability to share information on areal-time basis.andP;  MIS departments can provide the impetus formaking an organizational change on the corporate-wide level bymaking the change first.andP;  MIS departments should reorganize withthe customer in mind, forming small units that will work with usergroups to provide particular solutions.andP;  Any nonessentialactivities must be eliminated.andP;  Departments should provide onlythe highest-quality service to gain the appreciation of users, andcoordinate service carefully by communicating with customers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ReorganizationCompaniesCompetitionManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>